Id like to leave some feedback about the quality of care that I received during my last visit in the hope that this will make its way to the right people. While I normally visit the Takoma Park and Silver Spring locations, I went to the Greenbelt location today because the other two had no availability.    Dr. Pacheco was great and this is in no way a reflection of her. However, I think the CCI staff is in the wrong industry. When it came time to get my blood panel and breath test taken, the lab test was rude and unprofessional to say the least.    The medical assistant told me to write my name and dob on a cup for my urine sample. There were no markers or pens in the bathroom so I went to the lab and asked the tech if she had something I could use. Her response was just let me take your blood first, I will give you a label later. This alone shows poor bedside manners. I was then told to blow into a bag and was given a liquid to drink. Not aware of what I was being tested for and which tests were for which orders, I asked her what the liquid was for. She was unable to answer and said she needed to get someone to answer my questions. When the medical assistant walked in, she too said she did not know what the tests were for and responded with did the doctor not tell you?      As a patient, I have the right to ask questions to ensure Im receiving the right level or care. Knowing that a lab tech and medical assistant could not answer my basic questions was concerning. The lab tech was upset and flustered. It was clear she did not want to be there and I later realized that the lab was about to close and that was likely why she was not willing to help. She wanted to clock out. This is an internal problem. My appointment was at 3 p.m. and it is not my fault that I needed labs after. If the CCI team cannot provide good care after 3 p.m., they should stop scheduling after that time.    I understand people have their personal problems but it should not be at the expense of quality healthcare. I can no longer trust that these people are doing their job. I cannot trust that tech with putting a needle in my arm. So I decided to take my doctors order and will have to go to a LabCorp. While thats inconvenient, CCI Greenbelt did nothing to help improve my experience after telling them multiple times I was not comfortable with how they were handling things.      Id like to speak with someone to rectify this. Not for me, but for the sake of anyone else who might encounter the same.

My comment on the CCI Survey.     I like the fact that there was another person helping the receptionists. Even though there are 3 o 4 receptionists at a time the check in line is long and the wait time to check in is long too. But this time around I only waited the most a minute before the man with the mobile computer helped and directed me. The receptionist who checked me in, identified me by my full name and DOB and asked who I was seeing today. She checked me in quick and made sure my chart was up to date. The medical assistant is always so nice and polite. It is the same assistant that always takes my vitals. I believe she is Dr. Felsens main assistant. She always verifies first and last name and DOB before taking me back to my room. I love that Dr. Felsen always check my chart before walking into the room. She always well prepared and has an idea of my reason for the visit. She is a very tentative listener and you can tell that she crosses all her t and dots her i when it comes to ruling an illness out to get to the bottom of what is going on. Dr. Felsen does a great job in explaining why Im getting lab work, or referral, and why I am having such symptoms. She also explains with great clarity the next steps and treatments. She never leaves the room without verify that I understood every thing I was told. Before checking out, I was sent to the referral specialist, Shanelle. She explained why I was being referred, asked me if the location of the office was okay with me and made sure that my insurance was accepted in that office. Overall, from check in to check out everyone was respectful, efficient and precise. Its clear that in an overly busy office, management is doing a great job in training their staff on customer service.

2301 Greenery Ln APT 202  Silver Spring, MD 20996  A.QADER_SHARIFI@LIVE.COM  240-726-2342  July 19, 2023    CCI Management  8630 Fenton Street Suite 1200 , Silver Spring, MD-209103808      Subject: Disappointing Experience with Primary Physician Dr. Mahdav and Nurse Savannah at CCI    Dear CCI Management,    I hope this letter finds you well. I am writing to express my deep concern and dissatisfaction with the care I received during my recent visit to CCI. As a longstanding member of the CCI community, my family and I have always trusted your organization to provide quality healthcare services. However, my recent experience has left me questioning that trust.    My visit was intended for my annual physical check-up, during which I had hoped to address two specific health concerns  chest pain and testicular pain. Regrettably, what should have been a routine visit turned into a series of disheartening encounters that have prompted me to share my concerns with you.    Unpleasant Experience with Nurse Savannah:  Upon arriving at the CCI facility, I was greeted by Nurse Savannah, who guided me to the examination room. Unfortunately, her behavior was far from the compassionate and professional approach one expects in a healthcare setting. Not only did I have to wait for an extended roughly 45 minutes before seeing the doctor, but when I inquired about the delay, Nurse Savannah responded with the highest level of disrespect and raised her voice at me. This conduct left me feeling dismissed and disregarded as a patient, which is utterly unacceptable.    Inadequate Care from Primary Physician Dr. Mahdav:  When Dr. Mahdav finally came to examine me, I explained my concern about the pain in my testicle. To my dismay, he merely conducted a brief physical examination and concluded that he felt nothing unusual. I was taken aback by his lack of empathy and thoroughness in addressing my concern. As a primary physician, I expected Dr. Mahdav to demonstrate more attentive and comprehensive care, inquiring about the severity of my pain and exploring potential underlying causes.    To my disbelief, Dr. Mahdav suggested that I should go to urgent care if I continued to experience pain. This response felt dismissive and failed to address the fundamental role of a primary physician in diagnosing and managing health issues. As a patient, I place my trust in my primary physician to be my first point of contact for all health concerns, and I should not be directed elsewhere for basic medical evaluation.    Moreover, it was disheartening to see that my concerns were downplayed in the referral letter Dr. Mahdav provided after my insistence on the severity of my testicular pain. The letter merely stated that "The patient is very concerned about left groin pain please evaluate" which seemed to imply that my pain was merely a subjective concern rather than a legitimate health issue. This response left me feeling unheard and frustrated, as my primary physician should prioritize my health concerns and take appropriate actions to address them effectively.    Incomplete Physical Examination for My Wife:  During the same visit, my wife also sought her annual physical examination with Dr. Mahdav. However, to our dismay, the examination was incomplete, and she was asked to come back another time for a full physical assessment. We had made prior arrangements for her appointment, and this lack of thoroughness has added inconvenience and dissatisfaction to our overall experience.    Lack of Guidance Regarding Blood Cholesterol Diagnosis:  In addition to the issues mentioned above, I received a call from the hospital after my visit, informing me of being diagnosed with blood cholesterol. However, I was provided with no guidance or advice on how to manage this condition. As a patient, I expected to receive essential information on lifestyle changes, dietary recommendations, and potential risks associated with this diagnosis. This lack of information has left me feeling uninformed and concerned about how to take care of this health issue properly.    In light of these concerning experiences, I approached the facility's manager to express my concerns. While she attentively listened to my feedback and expressed empathy, she explained that she could address the complaint regarding Nurse Savannah but was not responsible for the physicians' section. Nevertheless, she assured me that she would convey my concerns to the relevant parties.   I am deeply disappointed with the level of care and service I received during my recent visit. The encounters with Nurse Savannah and the inadequate care from Dr. Mahdav have shattered my confidence in the care provided at your facility. My family and I have trusted CCI with our health, and it is disheartening to experience such lapses in care and professionalism.    I am writing this letter in the hope that you will take my concerns seriously and initiate appropriate actions to address these issues. As an organization committed to providing excellent healthcare services, I believe it is crucial for you to prioritize patient well-being and ensure that all patients receive compassionate, thorough, and professional care from your healthcare professionals.    I kindly request a thorough investigation into the matters I have highlighted, and I expect to be informed of the outcomes and any corrective measures taken. It is my sincere hope that my feedback will contribute to positive changes within your healthcare system and ensure a more satisfactory experience for patients in the future.    Thank you for your attention to this matter. I look forward to your response and hope to see improvements in the quality of care provided at CCI.    Sincerely,    Abdul Qader Sharifi

Dr. Hopkinson's compassion abounds every time we meet and this time was no different. Her expert advice and support is absolutely tremendous! Even though living with mental illness can be difficult, speaking with her does soften things sometimes. Her style is very calm, methodical & educational, which works for me. She truly listens first then provides meaningful and useful suggestions. During our sessions, her manner of asking me questions is very respectful. I am appreciative of that, because unfortunately society reacts negatively towards those with mental illness, as there is a stigma attached to what is actually a common (albeit sometimes misunderstood and unaccepted) condition. From the very beginning, Dr. Hopkinson created and has maintained a safe space for me to share. I feel comfortable talking about such personal issues and there is Peace of mind as well that she does her due diligence as a highly trained and experienced medical professional. For instance, during our last TeleHealth, I shared the difficulties of a particular challenge. During that same session, in real time, she emailed very useful information! She never ceases to amaze me at every visit. One thing that I am experiencing are landlord-tenant problems. Dr. Hopkinson and I discussed it and then there was an email from her while we were still talking about it!  That was valuable multi-tasking on her part and made me feel much better at the conclusion of our meeting. She went the "extra mile", so-to-speak, to assist with my issue. But that was not a surprise, well in the sense that her active listening and specific answers- which is very consistent, but in this case, it was amazing! That's what I mean about her compassion, and ability to always help without me even having to ask like I would if it was for a prescription refill or something else. More importantly, She's a very caring person that shows through both her words and actions. Again, I thank CCI for doing ALL it can to keep Dr. Hopkinson happy with what she requires to do her job to provide high quality service to her patients such as myself. But please do not forget about her needs too. She's been a doctor for a long time and I am sure that given all that happens medically within CCI (and the World at-large, not just about COVID-19) much of I am unaware, as I am only 1 patient that is lucky enough to have time with her during our appointments periodically, Dr. Hopkinson might want something to help her, too. I hope that CCI Management checks in with her about that, like ask about her well-being as I would be devastated to find out that she left CCI because of something internally with the healthcare practice and not because of her retirement. She is one of the best physicians that I have encountered in my lifetime (not that I am anyone). That might not be saying much to others, but it means a lot to Me and My Family! I take solace in knowing that my regular visits with Dr. Hopkinson is one constant in my Life, which can be filled with lots of uncertainty. Thank You for allowing Me to share yet again about her abilities to make me feel much better after we meet and honestly, keep having reasons to keep fighting. Dr. Hopkinson is a wonderful doctor and I hope that CCI Management knows that as I am speaking from firsthand experience. Her bedside manner is professional. She deserves to be recognized by CCI Management, Peers and others because she "brings a lot to the table" by being a part of The CCI Team. Thank You for allowing me to share additional comments. Dr. Hopkinson is a joy to telehealth with over these yearsat CCI Behavioral Health. We have not met in-person yet, not until our next appointment in June 2022. Her compassion and empathy, and most importantly advice comes through loud & clear over the telephone. Her voice and delivery style are a comfort and although this may sound "weird", I don't mind my doctor's appointments with her (unlike for example, a dental appointment. There is no "pain", if that makes sense and to keeping it in perspective based on her specialty as a psychiatrist.) I became her patient right before COVID-19, so we have always spoken via (my) mobile (her office telephone). She always listens to me intently before responding and never interrupts. Even when I am a little sad (& a time or two became emotional), She was very calming and made me feel much better. In fact, I always feel much better after our sessions. She is an excellent physician. I hope that CCI knows what a true Gem they have in Dr. Hopkinson. I would highly recommend her if someone is in need of a new doctor, for whatever reason, whether for the first time or they are searching for better healthcare. She's awesome! I fully believe that "selfcare" is NOT a "buzz word" or the latest fad because of COVID-19. It is of life long matter. My Father is a retired OB-Gyn, so I know firsthand, the meaning of superb bedside manner. Dr. Hopkinson is the epitome of what a good doctor looks like and sets an example of comprehensive care as well. During my care at one point, there was something she noted in my regular blood work, she consulted with my general practitioner, former CCI physician Dr. Lorri-Anne Burke (also a dynamite doctor!), to make a referral to a particular specialist doctor. I am happy to report all is well as it relates to that issue. That speaks to her expertise and skill level, attention to detail and the consistent care that she has provided me with from the very beginning. One of the most important things that we discuss each visit is my medication. I explained the exorbitant cost associated with maintaining my regime. She immediately suggested a different pharmacy in real time during one of our sessions and put a brand new prescription in electronically at that particular pharmacy. I picked it up that same afternoon! I was more than overjoyed. In fact, I had to ask the pharmacist was the co-pay price correct, because it was soo very inexpensive compared to what I had been paying at a different pharmacy, I could not believe it! I immediately called my Father to share my good news, excitement and most of all, relief that I could better afford my medicine (along with everything else in my budget) THANKS ALL to Dr. Hopkinson. That type of positive action is what I have come to expect and rely on from Dr. Hopkinson. But this information about cheaper costs at another pharmacy was above and beyond. I am in debt to her for that as obviously my medicine is critical to my overall healthcare. Dr. Hopkinson never forgets that when she does her job, about anything I am seeking. I am so appreciative to be her patient (not that I necessarily "love" needing mental health assistance, but at least since I require it; She is Top-Notch for that care!) I hope that CCI Management, her peers, and the medical boards that she receives certifications, are aware of her level of expertise as it relates to comprehensive healthcare. Even her staff, that I have spoken with, on her behalf, is kind and professional. Because honestly, I do not always enjoy speaking to other staff at any doctor's office, besides the doctor, in this case Dr. Hopkinson, but her staff that I have spoken with show a level of respect for her via their willingness (also positive interaction) to help me. That indicates again her professionalism to work with people that share her values and morals to provide excellent patient care, as I know that she opted to work with them to continue in her pursuits to be the best doctor that she's always been, even though I have only known her for a few years. It is easy to see that her work ethic is strong. Thank You for letting me share so much about my current experience with one of your CCI Providers. Again, Dr. Hopkinson is the Best! I am looking forward to meeting her in-person next month.

Yes, I had an appointment back in November with Dr.Hopkinson, my psychiatrist, and I tried calling Carmen Gomez several times to cancel. She never called me back after I called every day and left her several voice messages. I then called every week in December and in January and left voice messages. With no reply. I have been trying to get an appointment for a therapist since the spring of last year, to no avail. I have been without medication for a month, and left Carmen several messages stating so, again no reply. I called another location to see if I could find some help. When I got a person on the phone she heard about what was happening and she was so appalled that even though she doesn't work directly for behavioral health that she would be willing to help me straighten this out. I finally got on the phone with Carmen's supervisor but was offered no help in getting my medications. I had to suggest that the doctor send me scripts, which somehow she was not privy to that being the way things work? Indeed Dr.Hopkinson, when informed sent me my medication slips. Thank goodness for her. Mr.Bussi is a wonderful therapist, and Dr.Hopkinson is a fabulous Doctor. I am unsure who dropped the ball on this, but it several affected my mental health in a very bad way. I will be making a formal complaint  to the board of health of Maryland. Not out of malice, because very obviously you are understaffed. Carmen may not be at fault in all of this, and perhaps the BOH being contacted might find her some assistance in her duties. As she walked in with her bag of collection items to collect blood from my 5day old baby. I asked her if she was going to prick the babies foot. She said I usually draw the blood, but I can prick her foot if you want me too in a slight attitude.  Her response immediately had me on edge because I know youre not supposed to draw blood from a baby by the arm, especially not at 5days... and 8lbs so she proceeded to prep for the foot prick. Dismissing  patients assuming they have covid because they have symptoms that can well be anything else besides covid makes no sense.   My body temperature was taken and read under 97 degrees the day of my appointment. I had a high temperature 24 hours before that was under 99 degrees. So I was placed in a room that  was not ready to be used, it had not been disinfected, there was a couch in the middle of this room that was clearly being used as a break area.   I was surprised with a covid test as Im waiting for my appointment to take place. Next thing I know two doctors are ready to swab me. I was told if I came positive I would be contacted and if I came negative I would not be contacted.   This system is illogical because there is no follow up from the doctor to make up for the appointment missed or follow up to see if Ive gotten better at whatever I have . I can have an infection, a cold which would need medicine but the doctor is ready to assume that a low fever and a small headache that only lasted for one day is grounds to dismiss people for covid. I understand its difficult times but if everyone keeps being dismissed for a temperature under 99.0 degrees that lasted one day and a mild headache. How are people supposed to go to the doctors? will this encourage people to lie in order to get service? there must be more symptoms that merit testing. There was a huge SNAFU with making this appt. I normally go to Gaithersburg, but there were no docs avail this week and it was important I try to get lab tests or an opinion on how to treat my urgent ailment. I thought I made a phone appointment for 11:20am with an unknown dr who might be working from home. At 12:30 I got a call from silver spring saying I had missed my appt. I explained that I had insisted & verified phone appt, and they quickly rescheduled for 2:40pm. That made me feel better. At 2:50p I got a call from reception verifying my address and saying the dr/np would call in a few seconds. By 3:20pm I was agitated and called silver spring reception. I talked to someone at 3:35pm and she said the dr was finished w/previous patient and would call soon. I was frustrated, but the receptionist said to call her back in 30min if no one had called. That made me feel better. The dr/np called at 3:45pm. I really appreciated her time and insight and help. She was able to give me a great assessment I felt comfortable with and steps to heal I feel comfortable with. My big complaint is that the appointment was an hour behind schedule. I get being busy and falling behind schedule and unforseens, but +/- 1 HOUR is too much. That on top of the earlier mistake of scheduling an in-person instead of phone appt. was a big SNAFU of a day. On top of being really sick and low energy. In the end, I received the care I needed, but I was about to give up around 3:20pm. I really commend Dr Mouafu for shifting my state of frustration to deep gratitude. She listened very well and didnt offer anything I felt uncomfortable with. I suggest letting phone appts know how much time the dr might be off schedule. Like be ready 15 min before and 15min after or if you havent heard in 20min, give us a call.
